headline: This video does not show Saddam Hussein making a reference to COVID-19
fact_check_details: A video of former Iraqi dictator Saddam Hussein has been shared repeatedly on Facebook, Twitter and Instagram alongside a claim it shows him stating the US threatened to spread the novel coronavirus, COVID-19, in Iraq during a meeting in the 1990s. The claim is false; the video's audio has been doctored to include a reference to COVID-19; the original Associated Press archive footage does not include any reference to COVID-19.

headline: This video shows police officers arresting protesters in Hong Kong in August 2019
fact_check_details: A video has been viewed thousands of times in multiple posts on Facebook, Twitter and YouTube which claim it shows Chinese police arresting people infected with the novel coronavirus, COVID-19. The claim is false; the video shows police arresting pro-democracy protesters at a subway station in Hong Kong in August 2019.

headline: US President Donald Trump did not announce a coronavirus vaccine was 'ready'
fact_check_details: A video of US President Donald Trump and a top US pharmaceutical executive speaking at a press conference has been viewed thousands of times in multiple Facebook, Twitter and YouTube posts alongside a claim that it shows them announcing a vaccine for the novel coronavirus, COVID-19, was "ready" to be administered. The claim is false; neither Trump nor the pharmaceutical executive make any reference to a vaccine being "ready" for distribution; as of March 2020, the World Health Organization (WHO) states there is not yet a vaccine for COVID-19.

headline: Indian health authorities refute myth that juiced vegetables can cure COVID-19
fact_check_details: A post has been shared repeatedly in multiple posts on Facebook, Twitter and Whatsapp which claims a regional government in India has recommended that the juice of bitter gourd, a vegetable often used in traditional medicine, is an effective treatment for the novel coronavirus, COVID-19. The claim is false; Indian authorities dismissed the claim, calling it “absolutely false”; health experts said there is no evidence the vegetable is an effective remedy for COVID-19.

headline: Indian authorities refute 'fake' advisory which claimed disinfectant would be sprayed across India to tackle COVID-19
fact_check_details: A purported advisory has been shared repeatedly in multiple Facebook, Twitter and WhatsApp posts that claims a disinfectant will be sprayed into the air overnight in India in an effort to kill the novel coronavirus, COVID-19. The posts urge residents to remain indoors during the spraying. The claim is false; Indian authorities said the advisory was "fake" and that no such measure had been announced.

headline: This is an AFP photo taken during anti-citizenship law protests in Lucknow, India in December 2019
fact_check_details: A photo of a policeman throwing an object has been shared repeatedly in multiple Facebook and Twitter posts which claim it shows a policeman participating in sectarian violence in the Indian capital of Delhi in February 2020. The claim is false; the image is an AFP photo of a police officer taken in December 2019 during clashes with anti-citizenship law protesters in Lucknow, a major city in north India.

headline: This is an AFP photo of a policeman threatening a child with a baton during clashes in Bangladesh in 2010
fact_check_details: A photo has been shared tens of thousands of times in social media posts in India which claim it shows a Delhi police officer threatening a child with his baton during anti-citizenship law protests in the country’s capital. The claim is false; this photo actually shows a Bangladeshi police officer raising his baton at a child during a protest in Dhaka in 2010.

headline: Experts in India refute misleading claim that China-made Holi festival goods are infected with coronavirus
fact_check_details: A claim that Chinese goods imported for the Holi festival in India should be avoided because they are infected with the novel coronavirus has been shared multiple times on Facebook, Twitter and WhatsApp. The claim is misleading; the World Health Organization (WHO) told AFP that the virus does not last long on inanimate surfaces, so it is unlikely imported goods would remain infectious; the Toy Association of India told AFP the virus would not survive on a shipment of Holi festival items as the journey from China generally takes at least two weeks.

headline: Indian health authority refutes hoax report of coronavirus case in Uttar Pradesh district
fact_check_details: A claim that a man infected with an acute case of novel coronavirus has been admitted to a hospital in a town in Uttar Pradesh, India has been shared multiple times on Facebook and Twitter. This claim is false; the district’s health authority said there are no confirmed novel coronavirus patients in the area.

headline: Indian health authorities dismiss hoax report of novel coronavirus case in east Indian state
fact_check_details: A post has been shared multiple times on Facebook that claims a doctor in Purnea, a district in the east Indian state of Bihar, has identified a novel coronavirus patient. This claim is false; the local health authority said that there are no confirmed novel coronavirus patients in the area as of February 14, 2020. The doctor named in the misleading Facebook post also called the claim “baseless and false."

headline: This video shows workmen uncovering a bat-infested roof in the US state of Florida in 2011
fact_check_details: A video showing scores of bats nesting under tiles of a roof has been viewed tens of thousands of times in multiple posts on Facebook that it shows the cause of the 2019 novel coronavirus outbreak in China. The claim is false; the video has circulated online since at least July 2011 and actually shows repairs being made to the roof of a bat-infested house in the city of Miami in the United States.

headline: This is a 2015 Reuters photo of traffic in Beijing
fact_check_details: An image has been shared hundreds of times in Facebook posts that claim that it shows a massive traffic jam in southern India after a regional harvest festival. The claim is false; the photo was actually taken in 2015 by the Reuters news agency and shows a giant tailback on an expressway in Beijing, China.

headline: This is a 1998 Associated Press video of a US-British attack on Iraq
fact_check_details: A video has been viewed hundreds of thousands of times in Facebook and YouTube posts which claim it shows a US attack on the Iranian capital on January 8, 2020. The claim is false; the video was actually published by the Associated Press news agency in December 1998 and shows a joint US-British military offensive in Iraq.

headline: This footage has been taken from a video game
fact_check_details: A video has been viewed thousands of times in Facebook and Twitter posts that claim it is aerial footage of a US drone strike killing a top Iranian military commander General Qassem Soleimani "in Iran". The claim is false; the footage is actually from a military simulation video game; Soleimani was killed on January 3, 2020 by a US strike in Baghdad, Iraq.

headline: This is a photo of Shah Rukh Khan in London in 2012 -- police deny Khan was ever arrested
fact_check_details: A photo of Indian actor Shah Rukh Khan has been shared hundreds of times in multiple Facebook and Twitter posts that claim that it shows the Bollywood star being arrested at London’s Heathrow Airport on December 28, 2019 after attempting to protest in the UK against  India's new citizenship law. The claim is false; the photo has actually circulated online since 2012 in reports about Khan visiting the BBC office in London for an interview; London’s Metropolitan Police said that they had not arrested Khan.

headline: This old photo was taken during a March 2011 protest in the northern Indian city of Lucknow
fact_check_details: A photo has been shared hundreds of times in multiple Facebook and Twitter posts alongside a claim that it shows an Indian police officer stomping on the head of a student protester from New Delhi’s Jamia Millia Islamia university. The claim is false; the photo was taken during a protest in the northern Indian city of Lucknow in March 2011.

headline: This video shows the funeral of an Indian army soldier that was held a day before the Hyderabad attack
fact_check_details: A video has been viewed more than a million times in Facebook, Twitter and YouTube posts that claim the footage shows the funeral of a 27-year-old veterinary doctor who was gang raped and killed on November 27, 2019 in Hyderabad, a major city in southern India. The claim is false; the video actually shows the funeral of an Indian army soldier in a village in west India which was held on November 26, a day before the attack in Hyderabad.

headline: This video shows police in a different state hitting a suspect in an unrelated rape case
fact_check_details: A video has been viewed tens of thousands of times in multiple Facebook posts that claim it shows police beating a suspect in a high profile rape and murder case that happened in Hyderabad on November 27. The claim is false; the video actually shows police in the neighboring state of Andhra Pradesh hitting a man accused of rape; the footage had circulated online prior to the Hyderabad attack.

headline: Fact Check: Eight-year-old photo passed off as police atrocities on Jamia students
fact_check_details: ConclusionPicture is eight years old and from Lucknow

headline: Fact Check: Is this the video of US drone strike that killed Iranian general Soleimani?
fact_check_details: ConclusionThe video is a clipping of a video game and has nothing to do with Soleimani’s killing.

headline: Fact Check: Viral post saying Italians are throwing their money on the streets is false
fact_check_details: ConclusionThese are old pictures from Venezuela and have nothing to do with the Covid-19 pandemic

headline: Fact Check: Aishe Ghosh's hand injury is not shifting, the photo is morphed.
fact_check_details: ConclusionThe viral photo showing Ghosh’s right hand bandaged has been flipped. She was injured on her left hand.

headline: Fact Check: Irfan Pathan was meeting fans in Kolkata, not protesters at Shaheen Bagh
fact_check_details: ConclusionViral video is from Irfan Pathan’s visit to Kolkata

headline: Fact check: No, Nirmala Sitharaman never said onion price rise doesn’t matter to her
fact_check_details: ConclusionNirmala Sitharaman never said onion price rise doesn’t matter to her.

headline: Fact Check: These images of US soldiers' coffins don't show Iran's revenge
fact_check_details: ConclusionPhotos are quite old and have no relation with the recent attack.

headline: Fact Check: How a US warship pushed Navy Day into a whirlpool of controversies
fact_check_details: ConclusionThe image used in the Navy Day greetings is of a US warship

headline: Fact Check: Old pic of sick chicken passed off as coronavirus infected in Bengaluru
fact_check_details: ConclusionViral image of sick chicken is old and not related to coronavirus.

headline: Fact Check: No, this is not the PM of Italy crying over Covid-19 deaths
fact_check_details: ConclusionThe man seen crying in the picture is Brazilian President Jair Bolsonaro and the incident has nothing to do with the Covid-19 outbreak

headline: Fact Check: No, clapping together at 5 pm during Janta curfew will not kill coronavirus
fact_check_details: ConclusionThere is no proven evidence that vibration created by collectively clapping can destroy coronavirus.

headline: Fact Check: No, this is not the son of IB operative Ankit Sharma killed in Delhi riots
fact_check_details: ConclusionThe picture was taken at the funeral of one Mudassir Khan, another victim of the violence.

headline: Fact Check- Incident of a man kidnapped and raped by three women is not from Telangana
fact_check_details: ConclusionThe incident happened in South Africa. The image is of a different incident.

headline: Fact Check: Is this Rahul Gandhi lying on the ground after a trip-and-fall?
fact_check_details: ConclusionThe man seen lying on the ground is Robert Vadra, who had fainted during a prize distribution event

headline: Fact Check: Do not believe this hoax about the death of Kobe Bryant’s wife
fact_check_details: ConclusionIt is a hoax

headline: Fact Check: Old, unrelated video of bats streaming out from a roof linked to coronavirus outbreak
fact_check_details: ConclusionThe viral video is around nine years old and is from Miami, USA.

headline: Fact Check: Old photo of Rahul Gandhi and Arvind Kejriwal goes viral with misleading claim
fact_check_details: ConclusionThis is an old photo, taken at Rashtrapati Bhavan on January 26, 2018.

headline: Fact Check: Old video passed off as man in Shaheen Bagh spitting on food for distribution
fact_check_details: ConclusionThe video is at least two years old and not from Delhi.

headline: Fact Check: No, Putin has not unleashed lions on Russian streets to enforce Corona lockdown
fact_check_details: Conclusion This picture is from Johannesburg in South Africa and about four years old

headline: Fact Check: Porn pics used to cook up a story about rape by Indian soldiers
fact_check_details: ConclusionThe story described in the article is cooked up by using images from multiple unrelated websites.

headline: Fact Check: Taj Mahal being hosed down to welcome Donald Trump? No, this is not Agra
fact_check_details: ConclusionThe monument in the viral video is a replica of the Taj Mahal in Bhopal.

headline: Fact Check: Did police thrash accused in rape and murder of Telangana vet in public?
fact_check_details: ConclusionThe incident is from Chittoor in Andhra Pradesh where police are beating up a man accused of raping a Class 5 girl.

headline: Fact Check: No, this COVID-19 patient is not the wife of Canadian PM Justin Trudeau
fact_check_details: Conclusion Woman seen in the video is not the wife of Justin Trudeau but a COVID-19 patient from London

headline: Fact Check: Is Indira Gandhi posing with her husband and father-in-law in this photo?
fact_check_details: ConclusionThe photo is of Jawaharlal Nehru, Indira Gandhi, Russian artist Nicholas Roerich and Gandhi's aide Yunus Khan.

headline: Fact Check: Old video of pro-Khalistan rally passed off as anti-NRC stir in Punjab
fact_check_details: ConclusionVideo is three years old and has nothing to do with the anti-NRC stir.

headline: Fact Check: Love in the time of Corona? Know the truth behind this viral image
fact_check_details: ConclusionThis photograph was taken in Barcelona airport, Spain. No such news report of the Italian doctor couple found.

headline: Fact Check: This story about woman falling from Eiffel Tower is too good to be true
fact_check_details: ConclusionThe woman in the viral image never attempted suicide from Eiffel Tower. The viral story is partially true.

headline: Fact Check: Tarek Fatah loads up on fake again, drops a film clip to mislead on polio
fact_check_details: ConclusionViral video is a scene from a Pakistani film Load Wedding

headline: Fact Check: Before Trump’s visit, slum image from Mumbai passed off as Gujarat on social media
fact_check_details: ConclusionViral images have no connection with Gujarat.

headline: Fact Check: Did this man track down and brutally torture his three-year-old daughter's rapist?
fact_check_details: ConclusionThe man in the photo was arrested by South African police for allegedly looting and clashing with foreign residents

headline: Fact Check: Tarek Fatah passes off old video with communal slogans as recent one from Delhi
fact_check_details: ConclusionThe video is more than two years old and from Rajasthan’s Udaipur
